\details{
Authenticates automatically if no active Gmail session is detected.
\subsection{Threading}{

Gmail's \code{gm_create_draft()} does \strong{not} support \code{thread_id}. When
\code{draft = TRUE} and \code{thread_id} is set, \code{mc_send()} issues a warning
because the draft will not appear in the thread until manually sent
from the Gmail UI. Set subject to \code{"Re: Original Subject"} so Gmail's
thread-matching heuristic can place it correctly.

When \code{draft = FALSE} and \code{thread_id} is set, the message is sent
directly into the thread via \code{gm_send_message(thread_id = ...)}.
}

\subsection{Test mode}{

\code{test = TRUE} sends to yourself, strips CC, and ignores \code{thread_id}
to prevent accidental sends to real threads during development.
}

\subsection{Scheduled send}{

\code{send_at} runs a background R process on your machine. On macOS,
\code{caffeinate} is used to prevent idle sleep so the machine stays awake
until the email sends. The laptop lid can be closed as long as power
is connected.
\itemize{
\item \strong{Laptop powered on} — sends on time (caffeinate prevents sleep)
\item \strong{Laptop powered off} — process dies, email never sends
}

If caffeinate is bypassed and the machine sleeps through the send
window, a 5-minute grace period applies. Past that, the send is
\strong{skipped} to prevent stale emails firing unexpectedly.
}
